{"questionId":"2676716","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>An ice cream vendor investigates the relationship between the total number of children&nbsp;visiting the park and the number of ice creams sold, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>. The following table shows the data&nbsp;collected on five different days.</p>\n<table style=\"height:81px;width:489.578px;border-style:solid;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;width:138px;\">\n<strong>Total number</strong><br><strong>of children&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">y</mi><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">)</mo></math></strong>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:63px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>81</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:63px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>175</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:59px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>202</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:60px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>346</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:58.5781px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>360</mn></math></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;width:138px;\">\n<strong>Ice creams</strong><br><strong>sold <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">x</mi><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">)</mo></math></strong>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:63px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:63px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:59px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>23</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:60px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>35</mn></math></td>\n<td style=\"border-style:solid;text-align:center;width:58.5781px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>46</mn></math></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence, use your regression equation to predict the number of ice creams that the&nbsp;vendor sells on a day when the highest temperature is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>°</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to substitute their answer to part (a) into their regression equation for either&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0935114</mn><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>×</mo><mn>310</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>43053</mn><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4190</mn><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo></math>(accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>37</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo></math>or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>Award&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)A1FT</strong></em>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>37</mn></math>&nbsp;found from using&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>39</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>.&nbsp;<br><br>Award&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)A0FT</strong></em>&nbsp;for a correct&nbsp;<em><strong>FT</strong></em>&nbsp;answer that lies outside&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>46</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2676716","referenceCode":"23M.2.SL.TZ1.4c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, use your regression equation to predict the number of ice creams that the vendor sells on a day when the highest temperature is 25°C.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
